{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496996"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1452"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1452"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.24,0.08,0.03,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1452"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1452"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"759"},{"type":"tags","id":"1179"},{"type":"tags","id":"9168"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14415"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15030"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a painless swelling in her left groin. This has been present for about one year and initially did not give her any bother, but is now becoming rather uncomfortable. It used to go away at nightime but now is consistently present. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling is soft, non-tender and does not change in size with direct pressure. It is located below the inguinal ligament and lateral to the pubic tubercle (Image). There is no cough impulse. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Ultrasound scan","CT abdomen and pelvis","Hernia truss","Referral for surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with a femoral hernia. The location of the swelling below the inguinal ligament and lateral to the pubic tubercle is characteristic of a femoral hernia, distinguishing it from an inguinal hernia. Given the clear clinical presentation, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan. In straightforward presentations such as this, a consistent history and exam is all that is required to proceed with repair; no imaging required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFemoral hernias have a higher risk of strangulation compared to other types of hernias due to the narrow, rigid structure of the femoral canal. Therefore, all patients with femoral hernias are advised to undergo surgical repair, regardless of age, gender, or symptoms. This approach is particularly important when the hernia is irreducible, as it appears now to be in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if there was diagnostic uncertainty, particularly in obese individuals. However, in this case, the clinical presentation is clear enough to proceed with surgical planning without additional imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E would be excessive for diagnosing a femoral hernia when the clinical presentation is typical. It might be considered if there were concerns about other intra-abdominal pathology or complications of the hernia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate for a suspected hernia. This procedure is typically used for investigating suspicious lymph nodes or masses, not for hernias.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etruss\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated conservative measure once used for large hernial defects, particularly inguinal hernias. It is no longer recommended as a management option for femoral hernias due to the high risk of complications and the availability of safe surgical techniques.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, the definitive treatment for all femoral hernias is surgical repair. While the timing of surgery can depend on the progression of the hernia and patient preference, it is generally recommended to proceed with repair to prevent potential complications such as incarceration or strangulation of bowel within the hernia sac.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All patients with femoral hernias are advised to undergo surgical repair regardless of age, gender or symptoms.","Femoral hernias are located below the inguinal ligament and lateral to the pubic tubercle.","Femoral hernias have a higher risk of strangulation compared to other types of hernias."],"references":["McIntosh A, Hutchinson A, Roberts A, Withers H. Evidence-based management of groin hernia in primary care--a systematic review. Fam Pract. 2000 Oct;17(5):442-7. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11021907/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1452"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18437"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18437"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6cb53f4e-5a2c-407d-af1a-67abe0e1d1b1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6cb53f4e-5a2c-407d-af1a-67abe0e1d1b1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":418}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T09:18:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T09:18:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1452"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72832"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"